Better fix for file identifier bug addressed in previous commit

The problem was that the FileID constructor was being called directly, yielding
more than one FileID sharing the same hdf5 identifier. There must be a 1-to-1
correspondance between ObjectIDs and identifiers.

Fixes a file identifier bug

When accessing a file via the file property, followed by a file.close(), and
then opening a new file, the dealloc routines were improperly decrefing the
new valid file identifier. The fix was to check if an file identifier is valid
before setting its locked property to false.

Removes IDProxy level of abstraction around HDF5 identifiers.

There is now exactly one ObjectID instance in the universe for each valid
HDF5 identifier. ObjectIDs and subclasses thereof must be opened using the
"open" classmethod factory function.

Clean up objects registry when closing identifiers

Some object identifiers have a private _close method. This commit ensures that
when this method is called, the id proxies are invalidated and removed from
the registry. Some comments are also added explaining the origin of what had
been a confusing condition when accessing the registry.

Ensures invalid objects are not ressurected when HDF5 recycles ids

For example, when we close a file opened with default properties, any objects
in that file are also closed, and their identifiers become invalid. At this
point, HDF5 can recycle the identifiers. If h5py's ProxyID continues to hold
a reference to its original identifier, then an invalid object would suddenly
appear to come back to life. Worse, what was once an object representing
dataset A might suddenly represent an attribute B, or dataset C, etc.

In this change, when we close a file, we manage invalid id proxies so their
invalid state persists even after the HDF5 identifier has been recycled.

Replaces WeakValueDict IDProxy registry with a synchronized version

We've been synchronizing access in getproxy, but I think I overlooked
that when our IDProxys are garbage collected, a callback occurs which
removes the relevant entries from the WeakValueDict. That callback is
not synchronized, and so it appears to be possible for a race condition
to arise between getproxy and the garbage collector. This change
addresses the problem.

use a cython FastRLock to synchronize access to _objects registry

The cython version of FastRLock is documented at
http://code.activestate.com/recipes/577336/ . Operations are essentially
atomic, therefore acquiring the lock does not provide a break point where the
interpreter can turn execution over to another thread, which was a source of
problems due to hdf5 recycling identifiers.

With a regular threading.RLock, tests on an OS X 10.6.7 machine revealed
crashes in threaded/multiprocessing programs with python-2.7, but not with
python-3.2. The documentation indicates that the implementation and behavior
of FastRLock is similar to the threading.RLock provided by python-3.2, and
tests on OS X with the FastRLock have not resulted in crashes on OS X for
python-2 or python-3.

An additional benefit of FastRLock is performance, it is reportedly ~10x faster
than threading.RLock for non-congested cases, and 10% faster in congested
cases.
